{
  "text": "As highlighted in the findings of caudate-amygdala studies, considerable evidence suggests that the amygdala's interactions with other brain regions are most likely dependent on the type of learning/information being processed. Indeed, the caudate results discussed above were based on a larger set of studies indicating that the amygdala modulates the consolidation for both hippocampus-dependent spatial learning and caudatedependent cued or response learning. The amygdala's ability to modulate memory consolidation appears to be highly promiscuous, as studies have demonstrated its role in doing so across a wide variety of learning tasks [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . This modulation, however, most likely involves the regulation of activity and plasticity in many different downstream brain regions playing more selective roles during memory consolidation [CITATION_6] .",
  "correct_citation": {
